## Vision of statistical learning (teaching statement)

A proverb attributed to Confucius is 'Tell me and I forget. Show me and I remember. Let me do and I understand.' From my experience with teaching and learning, this rings true.

My work focuses on building tools that get help us statistics instructors and data analysts from telling to showing and involving.

Data visualization plays a key role in my work. Visualization's

---

## Tools for statistical communication and education

-   packages focused on communicating workflow

    -   flipbookr - Present code step-by-step and side-by-side with its output

    -   codeexplode - Create flipbooks from R scripts and R markdown 'flat files'

    -   exampleexploder - Bring package examples to life by applying exampleexploder and returning a code-movie version.

    -   ggmemory - Relive the coding process by presenting each execution in code history with its output

    -   doublecrochet - quote the contents of an .Rmd and present with output.

-   ggplot2 extension packages focused on visual statistical communication

    -   ggxmean - a suite of geoms to make visually displaying summary statistics easy

    -   ggsample - a suite of ggplot2 extension functions to quickly generate hypothetical outcome plots to aid in statistical discussions

    -   ggdistribution - fit data quickly to a variety of statistical distributions; stamp defined statistical distribution

-   ggplot2 extension packages focused on communication

    -   ggstamp - a suite of functions (stamp\_\*) that provide sensible defaults for annotation layers with ggplot2; positioning functions that help users build infographics/pictograms

    -   ggquiet - present individual elements of a ggplot step-by-step. Maintain alignment of the elements as you move through the steps.

